Ano ba talaga ang nangyayari sa'yo, Maya?
Maya quietly shrugs.
She no longer tries to explain.
She no longer defends herself.
Whatever she says...
She already knows it won't matter.
Jennifer mistakes her silence for indifference.
Ricardo mistakes it for stubbornness.
No one notices...
That Maya has simply stopped hoping to be understood.
The family continues living under the same roof.
Sharing the same table.
Passing each other every day.
But with every passing month...
Their conversations become shorter.
Their silences become longer.
And the distance between them grows so wide...
It no longer feels possible to cross.
The dining room is dimly lit.
Rain lightly taps against the windows.
The only sounds are the clinking of utensils and the faint hum of the ceiling fan.
The family eats dinner together.
Just like every night.
No one speaks.
Jennifer scrolls through her phone between bites.
Ricardo occasionally checks work messages.
Maya quietly eats.
Her eyes fixed on her plate.
Another ordinary evening.
Or at least...
That's what it looks like.
Jennifer suddenly locks her phone.
[signal arg="sfx:phone_lock"]
She looks at Maya.
May internship na ba kayong pag-uusapan next term?
Maya nods faintly.
Opo.
Jennifer smiles.
Good.
Mas mapapalapit ka na sa graduation.
Ricardo looks up from his meal.
Anak...
Naisip mo na ba talaga?
Pagkatapos mong grumaduate...
Ano'ng plano mo?
The question hangs in the air.
Months ago...
Maya would've hesitated.
She would've looked down.
She would've searched for the right words.
Tonight...
She answers almost immediately.
Without emotion.
Without uncertainty.
Without hope.
Mag-aabroad po.
Pause.
Maghahanap ng magandang trabaho.
Tapos...
Tutulungan ko kayo.
Jennifer smiles proudly.
She exchanges a satisfied glance with Ricardo.
Alam kong kaya mo.
Mabuti naman at malinaw na sa'yo.
Ricardo nods in approval.
'Yan ang gusto naming marinig.
Maya quietly nods.
She continues eating.
As though she had simply answered a routine question.
No one notices...
That she never once said what she wanted.
Only what everyone else wanted to hear.
The conversation continues.
Jennifer talks about opportunities overseas.
Ricardo mentions relatives working abroad.
They begin discussing Maya's future.
As though she isn't sitting at the same table.
Maya listens silently.
Occasionally nodding.
Occasionally responding with short answers.
Nothing more.
Inside...
She no longer argues.
She no longer questions.
Somewhere along the way...
She had stopped searching for her own answer.
It wasn't because she had finally found her dream.
It was because...
She had quietly accepted that her dream no longer mattered.
The family finishes dinner.
One by one...
They stand from the table.
No smiles.
No conversation.
Only silence.
The same silence...
That had become the loudest thing inside the Ilagan household.
[background arg="res://Art/Backgrounds/mayas_room.png" fade="0.7"]
Maya closes the door behind her.
The room is tidy.
Almost untouched.
Her desk remains covered with engineering books.
The space where her ipad once rested is still empty.
[signal arg="emotion_persist:lost:2"]
She stares at it for a brief moment.
Then quietly looks away.
She sits on the edge of her bed.
Reaches into her pocket.
And takes out her phone.
The screen lights up.
She opens a social media app.
Her thumb slowly scrolls.
One post.
Then another.
Then another.
Smiling faces.
Graduation photos.
Vacation pictures.
Perfect lives.
She keeps scrolling.
Expressionless.
Downstairs...
Jennifer smiles as she unlocks her phone.
[signal arg="sfx:phone_lock"]
She begins typing a new post.
"So proud of our daughter. One step closer to achieving her dreams."
She taps Post.
Almost immediately...
Notifications begin appearing.
"Congratulations!"
"So proud of her!"
Jennifer smiles with quiet satisfaction.
She sets her phone down.
Completely unaware...
That the future she proudly shares online...
Is no longer the future Maya chose for herself.
Upstairs...
Maya continues scrolling.
The glow of her phone illuminates her face.
It has become the only place...
Where she no longer has to answer questions.
The only place...
Where she can quietly disappear from reality.
[background arg="res://Mocks/Novel UI/image 3.png" fade="0.7"]
The house is quiet.
Almost too quiet.
The lights remain on.
Yet the home feels darker than ever.
[background arg="res://Art/Backgrounds/mayas_room.png" fade="0.7"]
Maya sits on the edge of her bed.
The room is illuminated only by the glow of her phone.
She scrolls.
One post after another.
Videos.
Photos.
Strangers laughing.
Friends celebrating.
Lives moving forward.
Her thumb never stops.
Her face remains expressionless.
She isn't looking for anything anymore.
She's simply passing the time.
Waiting for tomorrow.
[background arg="res://Art/Backgrounds/campus_courtyard.png" fade="0.7"]
The garage is nearly empty.
[signal arg="emotion_persist:lost:2"]
Ricardo remains at his workbench.
The shop should have closed hours ago.
Instead...
He continues working.
Tightening bolts.
Organizing tools.
Finding one more thing to fix.
Anything...
Except what is waiting for him at home.
His phone vibrates.
[signal arg="sfx:phone_notif"]
A message from Jennifer.
"Pauwi ka na?"
Ricardo glances at it.
Then slips the phone back into his pocket.
Without replying.
He returns to work.
[background arg="res://Mocks/Novel UI/image 3.png" fade="0.7"]
Jennifer sits alone on the couch.
The television plays quietly in the background.
She isn't watching.
Her attention never leaves her phone.
She scrolls through social media.
Perfect families.
Successful children.
Graduation photos.
She quietly presses the "Like" button.
Again.
And again.
And again.
She pauses at the photo she posted earlier of Maya.
Hundreds of reactions.
Comments praising her daughter.
[signal arg="emotion_persist:jealous:2"]
Jennifer forces a small smile.
Then continues scrolling.
[background arg="res://Art/Backgrounds/campus_hallway.png" fade="0.7"]
Ricardo quietly enters the house.
Jennifer briefly looks up.
Kumain ka na?
Oo.
Jennifer nods.
She returns to her phone.
Ricardo quietly walks past her.
Toward their bedroom.
Neither notices...
That Maya's bedroom light is still on upstairs.
Neither asks if she's awake.
Or how she's doing.
The house falls silent once more.
[background arg="res://Art/Backgrounds/mayas_room.png" fade="0.7"]
Maya finally stops scrolling.
She locks her phone.
[signal arg="sfx:phone_lock"]
The room goes dark.
For a brief moment...
She catches her own reflection on the black screen.
She stares at it.
The reflection feels unfamiliar.
As if she's looking at someone else.
Someone who stopped dreaming a long time ago.
She quietly places the phone beside her pillow.
Lies down.
And closes her eyes.
[background arg="res://Mocks/Novel UI/image 3.png" fade="0.7"]
The house stands still.
Upstairs...
A daughter lies awake in silence.
Downstairs...
A father buries himself in work.
A mother loses herself in endless scrolling.
Three people.
Three separate rooms.
Three separate lives.
Living beneath the same roof.
Yet farther apart than they have ever been.
[signal arg="emotion_persist:lost:2"]
It's measured in the conversations they never had.
The truths they never listened to.
And the love they forgot to show.
The Ilagan family never stopped loving one another.
But somewhere between expectations...
And the glow of their screens...
They stopped being present.
The house remains quiet.
The phones continue glowing.
No one looks up.
THE END.

